ChatGPT said:

Great! Let's go through a real example of how to use these two Git commands to create a rollback branch from a previous commit.
📘 What Does This Do?

git checkout <commit-id>       # Moves to an older state of your code
git checkout -b rollback-fix   # Creates a new branch from that older commit

You can then make changes or use this to apply Terraform and rollback infra.
💡 Example Scenario

Let's say your Git commit history looks like this:

$ git log --oneline

9f2d3a7 (HEAD -> main) Changed instance_type to t3.large  ❌
6c5a9f1 Added EC2 module with t2.micro                   ✅
4d8b2c0 Initial commit

You want to rollback to the commit where instance type was t2.micro → commit 6c5a9f1.
✅ Step-by-Step Git Rollback Example
🔹 Step 1: View the log

git log --oneline

Output:

9f2d3a7 Changed instance_type to t3.large
6c5a9f1 Added EC2 module with t2.micro

🔹 Step 2: Checkout the previous stable commit

git checkout 6c5a9f1

Now you're in detached HEAD state — you’re seeing the old version of the code.
🔹 Step 3: Create a new branch from this point

git checkout -b rollback-fix

Now you're on a new branch rollback-fix, pointing to the previous good commit.
🔹 Step 4: Run Terraform

Make sure you're in the Terraform directory. Then:

terraform plan
terraform apply

Now your infrastructure is rolled back to the stable version (t2.micro).
🔹 Step 5: Commit (if needed)

If you modified anything else (like version bump or comments):

git add .
git commit -m "Rollback to t2.micro config"

🔹 Step 6: Push and merge

git push origin rollback-fix
git checkout main
git merge rollback-fix
git push origin main

📌 Final Result

Your main branch is now back to the good state where EC2 was using t2.micro.
🧠 Summary
Command	Meaning
git checkout <commit-id>	Switch to old commit temporarily
git checkout -b rollback-fix	Create a new branch from that old point
terraform plan/apply	Apply the rollback on AWS
git merge	Bring changes back to main